(42, 5, 18, 40, 9, 2, 8, 'a man which was taken with a palsy', 'Healing of the Paralytic', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of a man sick of the palsy, showcasing the faith of those who brought him to Jesus. They highlight the miraculous act of Jesus forgiving sins and restoring health, illustrating his authority.', 'parallel', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 18, 41, 2, 3, 12, 'a man which was taken with a palsy', 'Healing of the Paralytic', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of a man with palsy, showcasing the faith of those who brought him to Jesus. The act of lowering the man through the roof in Mark parallels the effort described in Luke to bring him before Jesus.', 'parallel', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 18, 43, 5, 5, 6, 'a man which was taken with a palsy', 'Healing of the Infirmed', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of a man with a serious infirmity. In Luke, men bring a paralyzed man to Jesus, while in John, Jesus encounters a man with an infirmity for thirty-eight years.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 18, 44, 9, 33, 33, NULL, 'Connection of Healing and Palsy', 'Both passages emphasize a man afflicted with palsy, highlighting the theme of healing. In Luke, the focus is on the effort to bring the paralyzed man to Jesus, while in Acts, Eneas is described as having been bedridden due to his condition for eight years.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 19, 41, 2, 4, 4, 'let him down through the tiling', 'Healing Through Roof Access', 'Both passages emphasize the act of uncovering the roof to lower a sick man before Jesus. This connection highlights the determination of the friends to bring the paralytic to Jesus despite obstacles.', 'parallel', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 19, 40, 10, 27, 27, 'housetop', 'Connection of Housetops in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the significance of ''housetops'' in both passages. In Luke, the act of lowering the man through the housetop demonstrates a boldness in bringing needs to Jesus, while in Matthew, the call to preach from housetops emphasizes the importance of proclaiming truth openly.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 19, 5, 22, 8, 8, 'upon the housetop', 'Connection of Roof and Access', 'This connection highlights the significance of roofs in both passages. In Luke, the act of lowering the man through the roof emphasizes the physical structure''s role in accessing Jesus, while Deuteronomy underscores the importance of safety on roofs to prevent harm.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 19, 10, 11, 2, 2, 'upon the housetop', 'Connection of Roof Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize actions that take place on a roof. In Luke, the roof serves as a means to bring a paralyzed man to Jesus, while in 2 Samuel, David''s actions on the roof lead to significant consequences.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 19, 40, 24, 17, 17, 'upon the housetop', 'Connection of Housetop Imagery', 'This connection highlights the significance of the housetop in both passages. In Luke, the action of going upon the housetop signifies determination to reach Jesus, while in Matthew, the housetop serves as a warning to prioritize spiritual urgency over earthly concerns.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 19, 24, 19, 13, 13, 'upon the housetop', 'Connection of Rooftops and Houses', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of rooftops and houses. In Luke, the action of lowering a man through the roof contrasts with Jeremiah''s mention of houses on rooftops being defiled, highlighting different uses of rooftops in biblical narratives.', 'theme', 0.3, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 20, 44, 14, 9, 9, 'faith', 'Faith and Healing Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of faith in healing and forgiveness. In Luke, the man''s sins are forgiven due to the faith of others, while in Acts, Paul recognizes an individual''s faith to be healed.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 20, 40, 9, 2, 2, 'thy sins are forgiven thee', 'Forgiveness of Sins Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of forgiveness, as Jesus declares, ''thy sins are forgiven thee'' in both instances. This connection highlights the significance of faith in receiving forgiveness.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 20, 41, 2, 5, 5, 'thy sins are forgiven thee', 'Forgiveness of Sins Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of forgiving sins, with Jesus addressing the individual in need of healing. The phrase ''thy sins are forgiven thee'' in Luke parallels ''thy sins be forgiven thee'' in Mark, highlighting a shared theme of faith and forgiveness.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
